        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>New York&#44; April 17<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1881.<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd M. S. Morais<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>I beg leave to call your attention to a<lb/> Society&#44; lately organized in this city&#44; and called the<lb/> Mount Sinai Training School for Nurses.  This in&#45;<lb/>stitution has for its object the education of nurses for<lb/> the sick.  It provides for a class of Jewish women<lb/> who hitherto have been forced to engage in less con&#45;<lb/>genial work.  The Managers are especially anxious to<lb/> have the attention of Jewesses directed to the advan<lb/>tages of the school.  The pupil nurses will be<lb/> boarded and lodged gratuitously in a private dwelling<lb/> near Mount Sinai Hospital and will receive their<lb/> training in the wards of that Hospital and from<lb/> lectures and instruction given by the Superintendent<lb/> of the Training School and by the Visiting and<lb/> Resident Physicians of the Hospital.  Before for&#45;<lb/>mally entering the School there is allowed a<lb/> month of probation.  A suitable allowance will be<lb/> given to them for their personal expenses during<lb/> the two years of the course.  The nurses will have<lb/> time each day for exercise and rest&#44; every alternate<lb/> Saturday&#44; often an afternoon of leisure in the week&#44;<lb/> and a vacation of two weeks is allowed each year.<lb/>  At the end of their course&#44; a diploma is given to<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>them and they can then command twenty dollars<lb/> per week for their services in private cases.<lb/></p>
            <p>As it is the desire of the Managers to enable<lb/> Jewesses to obtain this remunerative means of<lb/> livelihood&#44; it is with this view that they write to<lb/> ask you if you will be kind enough to call the<lb/> attention of your congregation to the existence of the<lb/> Society and explain its object and workings.  It<lb/> is hoped that some women of your congregation will<lb/> avail themselves of this opportunity and also that<lb/> you will make personal effort to bring the ad&#45;<lb/>vantages that this Society affords to the notice of<lb/> such persons as you think will be glad to enter<lb/> this profession&#44; and also state that applications may<lb/> be sent to Miss Rich&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Superintendent &#34;Mt. Sinai Training School for Nurses&#44;&#34;<lb/>
                153 East 45<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Street&#44;<lb/>
                New York City&#44;<lb/>
                N. Y.<lb/>
                Trusting that we may obtain a speedy answer to<lb/> this appeal as the School will open on the 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> of<lb/> May.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am&#44;<lb/>
                Respectfully yrs<lb/>
                L. I. Hendricks&#44;<lb/>
                Secty.<lb/></p>
        </body>
